## Prerequisite:
mariadb-3.10.6, java-21-openjdk-headless

## To download Keycloak:
wget https://github.com/keycloak/keycloak/releases/download/26.5.6/keycloak-26.5.6.zip

## 1. Prepare the MySQL Database
On your MySQL server (which can be the Keycloak node itself or a dedicated DB node), run the following commands to create the environment:

## SQL
`- Create the database with UTF-8 support for international characters`

`CREATE DATABASE keycloak CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci;
- Create the Keycloak user`

`CREATE USER 'keycloak_user'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'YourSecurePass';
- Grant permissions (Keycloak needs to create/alter tables on first run` 

`GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON keycloak.* TO 'keycloak_user'@'%';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;`

---

## 2. Configure Keycloak for MySQL

Keycloak (Quarkus distribution) comes with the MySQL driver built-in, so you don't need to download a separate `.jar` file like in the old days.

Edit your configuration file: `/opt/keycloak/conf/keycloak.conf`
# Basic settings for running in production. Change accordingly before deploying the server.

# Database info
db=mariadb
db-username=keycloak
db-password=<db-password>

db-url=jdbc:mariadb://localhost:3306/keycloak?useUnicode=true&characterEncoding=UTF-8

# If the server should expose healthcheck endpoints.
health-enabled=true
metrics-enabled=true
http-access-log-enabled=true
log=file

# HTTP
http-enabled=true
http-port=8080
https-port=8443
https-certificate-file=/opt/keycloak/ssl/cert.pem
https-certificate-key-file=/opt/keycloak/ssl/privkey.pem
proxy=edge
hostname=<hostname>
hostname-strict=true
hostname-strict-https=true
hostname-port=443


## 3. Build and Initialize Keycloak

#After changing the database type in the config, you **must** rebuild the Keycloak optimized image.
cd /opt/keycloak
bin/kc.sh build

# Start it up (initial run)
# Note: Use start-dev first to ensure the DB tables are created correctly
bin/kc.sh start-dev`


